What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset we have contains 113937 entries and 81 attributes can be present for each entry. Each entry contains information like borrowers credit score and basic information like salary.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest appears to be the borrowed APR or Annual Percentage Ratio. I will be analyzing the attributes related to predicting a borrowers APR.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect the loan amount, employement status, period for loan, prosper score, credit score will be major factors in determining the APR for a person.

I will start by looking at the borrowerAPR column and how it is spread across the dataset.

In [25]:
# Convert ProsperRating and Employment Status into Categorical Datatypes 
pros_rate = ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA']
pros_classes = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = pros_rate)
df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = df['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(pros_classes)

status_order = ['Employed','Self-employed','Full-time','Part-time','Retired','Other','Not employed', 'Not available']
status_classes = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                    categories = status_order)
df['EmploymentStatus'] = df['EmploymentStatus'].astype(status_classes)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Variables explored above show the basic distribution in the dataset.
It appears that more borrowers have been taking loans for an amount under 15k.
Where people generally have a credit limit under 100k.
The stated monthly income also seems to lie under 20k for majority of lenders.
The dataset has outliers in most variables which might affect our analysis.
However, the distribution of our prime factor in consideration, the borrower APR seems multimodel.
It does not require any transformations

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The distributions of Monthly Income and Credit Limit are right skewed. But I don't feel in needs any transformations.
We can neglect the outliers and perform further analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The Heat Map pulled out significant correlations to be established amongst the variables.
The BorrowerAPR is negatively correlated to the ProsperScore indicating that a person with a better prosper score will reciever lower APR.
Lower amount of loan was associated with higher APR value.
Proper Rating suggests that the APR value decreases as the ratings get better. Stated Monthly Income does not seem to have any major effect on the APR value.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The available bank credit was positively correlated with major variables which indicates that more credit relates to higher incomes and loan amounts.
The borrowers with better employment status tend to having higher loan amounts.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It was observed that the relationship between Borrower APR and Loan Amount turned from being slightly negative to slightly positive with the betterment in Prosper Rating.
The loan amounts increased with the increase in term and rating. The increase in loan amounts with increasing term was exponentially higher for better ratings.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The most interesting and surprising observation was with the APR value when analyzed with term and rating. It decreased linearly for ratings HR till C with the increase in term and linearly increased with the ratings B till AA.
